      "targeted_response_start_logprob": 0.0
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure! Ibuprofen works by inhibiting the activity of cyclooxygenase enzymes, COX-1 and COX-2. These enzymes are responsible for converting arachidonic acid into prostaglandins, which are lipid compounds that play a key role in inflammation and pain signaling. By blocking these enzymes, ibuprofen reduces the production of prostaglandins, thereby decreasing inflammation and alleviating pain. It’s like putting a stop sign in front of the pain signals, preventing them from reaching the brain. This makes it easier for you to get back to your daily activities without being hindered by discomfort.",
      "source": "target",
